{"title_page": "Operation Crossbow", "text_new": "{{short description|World War II Allied operations against German long-range weapons}}\n{{For|the 1965 film of the same name|Operation Crossbow (film)}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict  = [[World War II]]<br />Operation ''Crossbow''\n|partof    = [[Campaigns of World War II#Strategic bombing campaign in Europe|Strategic bombing campaigns in Europe]]\n|image     = La Coupole, Helfaut-Wizernes.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption   = The [[La Coupole]] V-2 launch site at Wizernes in France was a \"Heavy Crossbow\" target\n|date      = August 1943&nbsp;\u2013 May 2, 1945{{sfn|Collier|1976|p=136}}\n|place     = [[Nazi Germany|Germany]], [[German occupation of France during World War II|France]], [[Belgium]], [[History of the Netherlands (1939\u20131945)|Netherlands]]\n|result    = Delayed use but \"limited effect\" on production<ref name=D-Olier />\n|combatant1={{flag|United Kingdom}}<br />{{flag|United States|1912}}<br />{{flag|Canada|1921}}\n|combatant2={{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n|commander1=\n|commander2=\n|strength1 = Sorties/bomb tonnage:<br />\n'''Total''': 68,913/122,133<ref name=Krause>{{cite thesis |last=Krause |first=Merric E |title=From theater missile defense to anti-missile offensive actions: A near-term strategic approach for the USAF |url=http://www.au.af.mil/au/awc/awcgate/saas/krause_me.pdf |format=pdf |publisher=[[Air University (United States Air Force)#Advanced Professional Military Education|School of Advanced Airpower Studies, Air University]] |date=June 1988 |page=11 |accessdate=2008-10-23}}{{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref><br />\n[[RAF]]: 19,584/72,141<br />\n[[USAAF]]: 17,211/30,350<ref name=AllWorldWars />\n|strength2= V-1 launches: 9,251 <br /><ref name=Charman />\n(8000 targeting London,<ref>{{cite book |last1=von Braun |first1=Wernher (Estate of) |authorlink=Wernher von Braun |author2=Ordway III, Frederick I. |author2-link=Frederick I. Ordway III |author3=Dooling, David Jr. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Space Travel: A History |location=New York |publisher=Harper & Row |year=1985 |edition=1st |origyear=1975 |isbn=0-06-181898-4 |page=105}}</ref> 2,448 targetting Antwerp){{sfn|Cooksley|1979|p=82}}<br />\nV-2 launches:<br /> 1664[[File:Flag of Belgium.svg|12px]],<br />1402[[File:Flag of the United Kingdom.svg|15px]],<br /> 76[[File:Flag of France.svg|12px]],<br /> 19[[File:Flag of the Netherlands.svg|12px]],<br />11[[File:Flag of Germany.svg|12px]] ([[Ludendorff Bridge]])\n|casualties1= Airmen/aircraft:\n* 700 [[Killed in action|KIA]]/154<ref name=Russell>{{cite |first=Edward T |last=Russell |year =1999 |url=http://www.airforcehistory.hq.af.mil/Publications/fulltext/leaping_the_atlantic_wall.pdf |format=pdf |title=Leaping the Atlantic Wall: Army Air Forces Campaigns in Western Europe, 1942\u20131945 |publisher= United States Air Force History and Museums Program |page=27 |url-status=dead |series= The U.S. Army Air Forces in World War II |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040627050452/http://www.airforcehistory.hq.af.mil/Publications/fulltext/leaping_the_atlantic_wall.pdf |archivedate=June 27, 2004 |accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref>\nBritish civilians killed/<br />seriously injured:\n* V-1: 6,184/17,981\n* V-2: 2,754/6,523<ref name=Charman>{{cite |last=Charman|first=Terry |url=http://archive.iwm.org.uk/upload/package/4/dday/pdfs/VWeaponsCampaign.pdf |format=pdf |title=The V Weapons Campaign Against Britain 1944\u20131945 |publisher=Imperial War Museum |accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref><br />\nFrench civilians: 3,600 killed, about 10,000 wounded by Allied bombing{{sfn|Zaloga|2018|p=92}}\n|casualties2=V-1: 4,261 destroyed<br />by [[anti-aircraft guns|AA guns]] (1,878),<br />[[Barrage balloon#World War II|barrage balloons]] (231),<br />and fighters (1,846):<ref name=Hillson />{{efn| [[Hawker Tempest]]: 638, [[de Havilland Mosquito]]: 428, [[Supermarine Spitfire]]: 303, [[North American P-51 Mustang]]:232, and others: 158}}\nV-2: 51/117 killed/wounded,<br />48/69 rockets/vehicles<br />damaged{{sfn|Collier|1976|p=135}}\n}}\n'''''Crossbow''''' was the [[code name]] in [[World War II]] for Anglo-American operations against the German [[V-weapons|long range reprisal weapons]] (V-weapons) programme. The main V-weapons were the  [[V-1 flying bomb]] and [[V-2 rocket]] \u2013 these were launched against Britain from 1944 to 1945 and used against European targets as well.<ref name=D-Olier />{{failed verification|reason=Crossbow not mentioned in source|date=March 2020}} It included strategic operations against research and development of the weapons, their manufacture, transportation and attacks on their launch site, and fighter intercepts against missiles in flight.<ref name=D-Olier>{{cite |last1=D'Olier |first1=Franklin |<!-- |author2=Alexander |author3=Ball |author4=Bowman |author5=Galbraith |author6=Likert |author7=McNamee |author8=Nitze |author9=Russell |author10=Searls |author11=Wright --> | date = September 30, 1945 |section=The Secondary Campaigns | section-url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/AAF/USSBS/ETO-Summary.html#page12 |via=Hyperwar Foundation |title=United States Strategic Bombing Survey, Summary Report (European War) |accessdate= March 23, 2020 |page=12|quote=<!--''The bombing of the launching sites being prepared for the V weapons delayed the use of V-l appreciably. The [[Bombing of Peenem\u00fcnde in World War II|attacks on the V-weapon experimental station]] at [[Peenem\u00fcnde]], however, were not effective; [[V-1 flying bomb|V-l]] was already in production near [[Bombing of Kassel in World War II|Kassel]] and [[V-2 rocket|V-2]] had also been moved to an [[Mittelwerk|underground plant]]. -->}}</ref>{{Rp|7}}\n\nInitial intelligence investigations in 1943 into the progress of German long range weapons was carried out under the code name '''Bodyline'''. On 15 November, a larger operation was set up under the name  ''Crossbow''.{{sfn|Gruen|1998|p=4}} [[Post-war]], Crossbow operations became known as \"Operation Crossbow\" particularly following the  [[Operation Crossbow (film)|1965 film of the same name]].\n\n== Strategic bombing ==\n{{Main|Combined Bomber Offensive}}\n[[File:Peenemunde test stand VII.jpg|left|thumb|[[Peenem\u00fcnde]] [[Test Stand VII]]]]\nIn May 1943 Allied surveillance observed the construction of the first of eleven large sites in northern France for secret German weapons, including six for the [[V-2 rocket]]. In November it discovered the first of 96 \"ski sites\" for the [[V-1 flying bomb]].\n\nOfficials debated the extent of the German weapons' danger; some viewed the sites as decoys to divert Allied bombers, while others feared [[chemical warfare|chemical]] or [[biological warfare|biological]] warheads.<ref name=\"levine1992\">{{cite book | title=The Strategic Bombing of Germany, 1940\u20131945 | publisher=Praeger | last=Levine |first= Alan J. | year=1992 | location=Westport, Connecticut | pages=136\u2013139 | isbn=0-275-94319-4}}</ref> When reconnaissance and intelligence information regarding the V-2 became convincing, the [[Churchill War Ministry|War Cabinet]] [[Bombing of Peenem\u00fcnde in World War II#Cabinet Defence Committee (Operations)|Defence Committee (Operations)]] directed the campaign's first planned{{efn| The June 1943 [[Operation Bellicose]] was not targeted against German long-range weapons, but happened to be the first bombing of a German long-range weapon facility (the [[Luftschiffbau Zeppelin|Zeppelin Werk]]). Likewise, an October 22/23, 1943, RAF [[Area bombing directive|city bombing]] wrecked homes of workers employed at the [[Fieseler|Gerhard Fieseler Werke]], delaying both their transfer to the new V-1 plant at [[Rothwesten]] and, as a result, \"the final trials of the [V-1] weapon's power unit, control-gear, diving mechanism, compass and air-log\" until February{{Rp|180}} (a \"three or four\" month delay of V-1s).<!--ref name=D-Olier/>(cited by Mets p. 239, which has the \"three or four\" numbers)--> Also, a few V-2 centre sections had been assembled by the [[Raxwerke]] when a November 2, 1943, [[Fifteenth Air Force]] mission targeting the nearby [[Messerschmitt]] fighter aircraft plant hit the Raxwerke.{{sfn|Ordway|Sharpe|1979|p=74,171}}}} raid (the [[Operation Hydra (1943)|Operation Hydra]] attack on [[Peenem\u00fcnde]] in August 1943).<ref name=Neufeld>{{cite book |last=Neufeld|first=Michael J|title=The Rocket and the Reich: Peenem\u00fcnde and the Coming of the Ballistic Missile Era|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780029228951|url-access=registration|year=1995|publisher=The Free Press|location=New York|isbn=|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780029228951/page/198 198]}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Operation Hydra, a few ''Crossbow'' attacks were conducted on the \"Heavy Crossbow\"<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sanders |first=T.R.B. (Sanders Mission) |date=February 1945 |title=Investigations of the Heavy Crossbow Installations in Northern France |url=http://janus.lib.cam.ac.uk/db/node.xsp?id=EAD%2FGBR%2F0014%2FDSND%202%2F3 |accessdate=2007-05-16}}</ref> bunkers of [[Blockhaus d'\u00c9perlecques|Watten]] (V-2) and [[Fortress of Mimoyecques|Mimoyecques (V-3)]] from August and November 1943 respectively.<ref name=Carter1>{{cite book |last1=Carter |first1=Kit C |last2=Mueller |first2= Robert |year=1991 |title=The Army Air Forces in World War II: Combat Chronology 1941\u20131945 |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/1454964/US-Air-Force-wwii-combat-chronology |via=[[Scribd]] |location=Washington DC |publisher=Center for Air Force History |pages= |isbn=1-4289-1543-5 |accessdate=2010-03-04}}{{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> \"Crossbow Operations Against Ski Sites\" began on December 5 with the \"Noball\" code name used for the targets (e.g., 'Noball 27' was the {{sic|Ailly-le-Vieux-Clocher}} site,{{sfn|Cooksley|1979|p=49}} \"Noball No. 93\" was in the [[Cherbourg]] area, \"Noball No. 107\" was at Grand Parc, and \"Noball V1 site No.147\" was at [[Ligescourt]]).\n\nThe US formed its own Crossbow Committee under General Stephen Henry (New Developments Division) on December 29, 1943,<!--SOURCE: Zaloga: V-Weapon sites, p. 29--> and the US subsequently developed bombing techniques for ski sites in February/March 1944 at the [[Operation Crossbow Site|Air Corps Proving Ground]].\n\nA mid-1944 [[Project Danny|plan for US Marine Corps aircraft to attack V-1 launch sites from aircraft carriers]] fell victim to inter-service rivalry \u2013 being opposed by the Army.\nV-2 facilities were also bombed in 1944, including smaller facilities such as V-2 storage depots and [[liquid oxygen]] plants, such as the [[Mery-sur-Oise]] V-2 storage depot<ref name=AllWorldWars>{{cite web |title=Total Crossbow Offensive Effort by Air Forces |url=http://www.allworldwars.com/V-Weapons%20Crossbow%20Campaign.html#10 |format= |work=V-Weapons (Crossbow) Campaign |publisher=AllWorldWars.com |accessdate=2009-03-22}}</ref> on August 4, 1944 and, by the [[Eighth Air Force]], which bombed five cryogenic liquid oxygen plants in Belgium on August 25, 1944 but aborted the next days attack on plants \"at La Louviere, Torte and Willebroeck, Belgium\" due to cloud.<!--ref name=McKillop/--><!-- The V-2 launch area at [[Wassenaar|Eikenhorst]] was attacked by RAF Bomber Command dropping 172 tons of bombs, with a lesser amount on the Raaphorst area.{{sfn|Ordway|Sharpe|1979|p=263}}-->\n\n=== Bombing priority ===\nAt the request of the British War Cabinet, on April 19, 1944,{{sfn|Gruen|1998|p=24}} [[General Eisenhower]] directed ''Crossbow'' attacks to have absolute priority over all other air operations, including \"wearing down German industry\" and [[Area bombing directive|civilian morale]]{{sfn|Collier|1976|p=46}} \"for the time being\", which he confirmed after the V-1 assault began on the night of June 12/13, 1944 saying to [[Arthur Tedder]] \"with respect to ''Crossbow'' targets, these targets are to take first priority over everything except the urgent requirements of the Overlorf [invasion of Normandy] battle; this priority to obtain until we can be certain that we have definitely gotten the upper hand of this particular business\".<ref name=Carter>{{cite book |last1=Carter |first1=Kit C. |last2=Mueller |first2= Robert |title=The Army Air Forces in World War II |url= https://books.google.com/?id=RjzLqxg6KlAC&pg=PT579 |publisher=Center for Air Force History |page=527 |accessdate=2009-01-10 |isbn=978-1-4289-1543-5 |quote=Mets' p. 389  gives the date as June 29}}\n<br />{{cite  |last=Eisenhower |first=Dwight D. |authorlink=Dwight Eisenhower |date=June 29, 1944 |title=Memorandum, Eisenhower to Tedder\n|work= |location=[[Eisenhower Presidential Library]] |at= Pre-Presidential File Box 115}}</ref>\nThe launches surprised the Allies, who had believed that the earlier attacks on the sites had eliminated the danger. The British, who had not expected German bombing of Britain to resume so late in the war, were especially upset. Some suggested using gas on the launch sites, or even executing German civilians as punishment.{{r|levine1992}}\n\n[[Carl Spaatz]], commander of [[United States Strategic Air Forces in Europe|U.S. Strategic Air Forces in Europe]] (USTTAF), responded on June 28<ref>{{cite |last=Spaatz |first=Carl |authorlink=Carl Spaatz |date=June 28, 1944 |title=Memorandum, Spaatz to Eisenhower |at=Pre-Presidential File Box 115 |location=[[Eisenhower Presidential Center|Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library]]}}</ref> to \"complain that ''Crossbow'' was a 'diversion' from the main task of wearing down the Luftwaffe and bombing German industry\" for the [[Combined Bomber Offensive]], and to recommend instead that ''Crossbow'' be a secondary priority since \"days of bad weather over Germany's industrial targets would still allow enough weight of attack for the rocket sites and the lesser tactical crises.\"<ref name=Eisenhower />{{Rp|349}} By July 10, Tedder had published a list of Crossbow targets which assigned 30 to [[RAF Bomber Command]], six to the tactical  [[Allied Expeditionary Air Force]], and 68 to Spaatz' USSTAF; after which Spaatz again complained,<ref>{{cite book |last=Mets |first=David R. |year=1997 |edition=paperback |origyear=1988 |title=Master of Airpower: General Carl A. Spaatz |page=239 |isbn=0-89141-317-0}}</ref>{{Rp|239}} so Eisenhower allowed \"spare\" bombing of non-Crossbow targets: \"Instructions for continuing to make ''Crossbow'' targets our first priority must stand, but ... when ... the entire strategic forces cannot be used against ''Crossbow'', we should attack\u2014(a) [[Operation Pointblank|Aircraft industry]], (b) [[Oil Campaign of World War II|Oil]], (c) [[Schweinfurt\u2013Regensburg mission|ball bearing]] [[German language|(German)]]: [[ZF Sachs|Kugellagerwerke]], (d) Vehicular production\" (Eisenhower, July 18).<ref name=Eisenhower />{{Rp|349}}\n\nNonetheless, over a quarter of the Combined Bomber Offensive's tonnage of bombs were used against V-weapon sites in July and August; many of the attacks were ineffective, as they were against unused sites rather than the launchers themselves. Spaatz unsuccessfully proposed that attacks concentrate on the Calais electrical grid, and on gyrocompass factories in Germany and V-weapon storage depots in France. The gyrocompass attacks, along with targeting liquid oxygen tanks (which the Allies knew the V-2 needed), might have been very effective against the missiles.{{r|levine1992}} On August 25, 1944, the Joint Crossbow Target Priorities Committee (established July 21)<ref name=Craven>{{cite book |editor-last=Craven |editor-first=Wesley Frank |editor2=Cate, James Lea |title=(Volume 3) Europe: Argument to V-E Day |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jTXWGhwBacAC&pg=PA530 |work=The Army Air Forces in World War II|page=535 |isbn=978-0-912799-03-2 |date=January 1983 }}</ref> prepared the \"Plan for Attack on the German Rocket Organization When Rocket Attacks Commence\"\u2014in addition to bombing of storage, liquid-oxygen, and launch sites; the plan included aerial reconnaissance operations.{{sfn|Gruen|1998|p=37}}\nFollowing the last V-1 launch from France on September 1, 1944, and since the expected V-2 attacks had not begun, ''Crossbow'' bombing was suspended on September 3{{sfn|Gruen|1998|p=34}} and the [[Oil Campaign of World War II|campaign against German oil facilities]] became the highest priority.\n\nThe V-1 threat from [[occupied France]] ended on September 5, 1944, when elements of the [[The Royal Canadian Hussars (Montreal)|7th Canadian Reconnaissance Regiment]] and the [[3rd Canadian Infantry Division]] contained the German military units of the [[Nord-Pas de Calais]] area with their surrender following on September 30.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hyrman |first=Jan |title=Operation Undergo: The Capture of Calais & Cap Griz Nez |work=Clearing the Channel Ports |url=http://www.nasenoviny.com/DunkirkENUndergo.html |accessdate=2008-06-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Resumption of bombing ===\n''Crossbow'' bombing resumed after the first [[V-2 rocket|V-2]] attack and included a large September 17 raid on Dutch targets suspected as bases for [[Heinkel He 111]]s, which were air-launching V-1s.{{sfn|Gruen|1998|p=37}} Modified V-1s (865 total) were air-launched from September 16, 1944 to January 14, 1945.<ref name=Pocock>{{cite book |last=Pocock|first=Rowland F|title=German Guided Missiles of the Second World War|year=1967|publisher=Arco Publishing Company, Inc.|location=New York|page=104}}</ref>{{Rp|104}} The British had initially considered that an earlier July 18\u201321, 1944 effort of 50 air-launched V-1s had been ground-launched from the [[Low Countries]], particularly near [[Ostend]].{{Rp|256}} In addition to air-launched V-1s, launches were from ramps built in the province of [[South Holland]], the Netherlands in 1945.\n\nAllied reconnaissance detected two sites at [[Vlaardingen]] and [[Ypenburg]], and along with a third at [[Delft]], they launched 274 V-1s at London from March 3\u201329. Only 125 reached the British defences, and only thirteen of those reached the target area. Three additional sites directed their fire on Antwerp. After using medium bombers against V-2 launch site in the [[Haagse Bos]] on March 3, the RAF attacked the Holland V-1 sites with two squadrons. An [[RAF Fighter Command]] unit used Spitfires against Ypenburg on March 20 and 23, while a [[RAF Second Tactical Air Force|2nd Tactical Air Force]] unit used Typhoons against Vlaardingen on March 23. Counterattacks on Holland's V-1 and V-2 sites ended on April 3, and all ''Crossbow'' countermeasures ended on May 2 with the [[end of World War II in Europe]].{{sfn|Collier|1976|p=133\u20136}}\n\n[[File:Spitfire Tipping V-1 Flying Bomb.jpg|thumb|A Spitfire tipping the wing of a V-1 to disrupt the missile's automatic pilot.]]\n\n== V-1 defence ==\n{{Main|V-1 flying bomb#Countermeasures|Operation Diver}}\nOn January 2, 1944, Air Marshall [[Roderic Hill]], Air Officer Commander-in-Chief of [[Air Defence of Great Britain]] submitted his plan to deploy 1,332 guns for the defence of [[London]], [[Bristol]] and [[the Solent]] against the V-1 \"Robot Blitz\" (the \"Diver Operations Room\" was located at [[RAF Biggin Hill]]).{{sfn|Collier|1976|p=96,161}} Against V-1s that had not run out of fuel or veered off course<!--Gruen 28--> the British deployed select units of [[RAF Fighter Command#Invasion of Europe|Fighter Command]] ([[No. 150 Wing RAF]]) operating high-speed fighters, the [[anti-aircraft guns]] of [[Anti-Aircraft Command]], and approximately 1,750 [[barrage balloon]]s of [[Balloon Command]] around London.<ref name=Hillson>{{cite journal\n |last=Hillson |first=Franklin J. (Maj) |date=Summer 1989 |title=Barrage Balloons for Low-Level Air Defense |url=http://www.airpower.maxwell.af.mil/airchronicles/apj/apj89/hillson.html |work=Air Chronicles; [[Air University (United States Air Force)#Air Force Research Institute|Airpower Journal]] |accessdate=2007-05-07 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070501062111/http://www.airpower.maxwell.af.mil/airchronicles/apj/apj89/hillson.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-05-01}}</ref>\n\n\"Flabby\" was the code name for medium weather-conditions when fighters were allowed to chase flying bombs over the gun-belt to the balloon line,{{sfn|Cooksley|1979|p=197}} and during Operation ''Totter'', the [[Royal Observer Corps]] fired \"Snowflake\" illuminating rocket flares from the ground to identify V-1 flying bombs to RAF fighters.{{sfn|Cooksley|1979|p=102}} After the  Robot Blitz<ref name=Hill>{{cite journal\n |last= Hill |first=Roderic |authorlink=Roderic Hill |date=October 19, 1948 | title=Air Operations by Air Defence of Great Britain and Fighter Command in Connection with the German Flying Bomb and Rocket Offensives, 1944\u20131945 |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/38437/supplement/5585 |format=pdf |accessdate=2009-04-28 |journal=[[London Gazette]] |location= |pages=}}{{Verify source|\"Connection\" does not seem to appear in the London Gazette for that date|date= April 2009}}</ref> began on the night of June 12/13, 1944, [[V-1 flying bomb#Countermeasures|an RAF fighter first intercepted a V-1 on June 14/15]]. Moreover, anti-aircraft guns increased the rate of downed V-1s to 1 per 77 rounds fired after \"the first few weeks{{When|date= February 2009}}<!-- THE Proximity fuse WIKIARTICLED DOESN'T IDENTIFY THE DATE --> of [[proximity fuse]] operation\" ([[Reginald Victor Jones]]).<ref name=Jones>{{cite book |last=Jones |first=R.V |authorlink= Reginald Victor Jones |year=1979 |title=Most Secret War: British Scientific Intelligence 1939\u20131945 |publisher=Coronet Books (Hodder and Stoughton) |location=London UK |page=428}}</ref> By June 27, \"over 100,000 houses had been damaged or destroyed by the V-1&nbsp;... and shattered sewage systems threatened serious epidemics unless fixed by winter.\"<ref name=Eisenhower>{{cite book |last=Eisenhower |first=David |authorlink=David Eisenhower |year=1991 |origyear=1986 |title=Eisenhower: At War 1943\u20131945 |location=New York |publisher=Wings Books |isbn=0-517-06501-0 |page=349}}</ref>\n\nOf the 638 air-launched V-1s that had been observed, guns and fighters downed 403 and the remainder fell in the [[Historical and alternative regions of England#World War II|London Civil Defence Region]] (66), at [[Manchester]] (1), or elsewhere (168, [[Double Cross System#V-weapons deception|including Southampton on July 7]]).{{sfn|Collier|1976|p=131}} Additionally, the gunners on [[No. 619 Squadron RAF#Commanding officers|W/Cdr. S.G. Birch's]] Lancaster claimed they downed a V-1 over the target area on a March 3, 1945, raid on the [[Ladbergen]] aqueduct.<!--(Ladbergen is TBD miles off the path from the Dutch launch sites to Antwerp)-->\n\n== V-2 counter-measures ==\n{{Main|V-2 rocket#countermeasures}}\n\nThe British intelligence services (Secret Intelligence Service and Air Ministry\u2019s Scientific Intelligence Office) were monitoring German rocket artillery research and information received by bugging high-ranking German prisoners-of-war increased focus on activities at Peenemunde.\nIn response to discussions by the  vice-chiefs of staff on the subject of German long range rocket developments, in April 1943 [[Duncan Sandys]] was given the responsibility of investigating how far Germany had progressed.<ref>Gruen, 1998</ref> Under the codename Bodyline, investigations by SIS, the Combined Services Detailed Interrogation Centre, and the Photographic Reconnaissance Unit were able to confirm existence of rocketry activities at Peenemunde and Sandys reported his findings to the chiefs of staff that the Germans were developing rockets, were probably well-advanced and countermeasures should be studied<ref>Gruen, 1998</ref>\n\nThe Bodyline Scientific Committee (19 members, including [[Duncan Sandys]], [[Edward Victor Appleton]], [[John Cockcroft]], [[Robert Watson-Watt]]) was formed in September 1943 regarding the suspected V-2 rocket. After the 1944 [[Sweden in World War II#The B\u00e4ckebo rocket|crash of a test V-2 in Sweden]], \"transmitters to jam the guidance system of the rocket\" were prepared.<ref name=Wooff>{{cite web |author=Jeff Cant |title=Fifty years of transmitting at BBC Woofferton: 1943\u20131993 |year=2006 |url=http://www.bbceng.info/Operations/transmitter_ops/Reminiscences/Woofferton/woof50y-v2.pdf |format=pdf |page=6 |accessdate=2014-03-19}}</ref> A British [[sound-ranging]] system provided \"trajectory [data] from which the general launching area could be determined\", and the microphone(s) in [[East Kent]] reported the times of the first V-2 strikes on September 8, 1944: 18:40:52 and 18:41:08.{{sfn|Ordway|Sharpe|1979|p=251}}\n\nIn November 1943, the Bodyline committee handed over the tasks to the [[Air Ministry]] as the extent of the issue became clear.\n\nOn March 21, 1945, the Pile's plan for the \"Engagement of Long Range Rockets with AA Gunfire\" which called for anti-aircraft units to fire into a radar-predicted airspace to intercept the V-2 was ready, but the plan was not used due to the danger of shells falling on Greater London.{{sfn|Ordway|Sharpe|1979|p=262}}\n\nUnlike the V-1 which was of comparable speed to a fighter, the velocity and trajectory of a V-2 made aircraft interception and impossibility. Happenstance instances of Allied aircraft enountering launched V-2 rockets include: October 29, 1944, Lieutenants Donald A. Schultz and Charles M. Crane in a [[Lockheed P-38 Lightning]] attempted to photograph a launched V-2 above the trees near the [[River Rhine]],<ref name=Kennedy>Kennedy, p4</ref> January 1, 1945, a [[4th Fighter Group]] pilot aloft over the northern flightpath for attacking elements of five German fighter wings on ''[[Unternehmen Bodenplatte]]'' that day, observed a V-2 \"act up for firing near [[Lochem]] ... the rocket was [[Meillerwagen|immediately tilted from 85 deg. to 30 deg\"]],{{sfn|Ordway|Sharpe|1979|p=256}}, and on February 14, 1945, a [[No. 602 Squadron RAF]] Spitfire Mk XVI pilot, [[Raymond Baxter]]'s colleague \"Cupid\" Love, fired at a V-2 just after launch.{{sfn|Cooksley|1979|p=162}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Den Haag (The Hague) \u2013 Wassenaar \u2013 Hoek van Holland |url=http://www.v2rocket.com/start/deployment/denhaag.html |work=A-4/V-2 Resource Site |publisher=V2Rocket.com |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref>\n\nAfter the last combat V-2 launch on March 27, 1945, the British discontinued their use of radar in the defence region to detect V-2 launches on April 13.{{sfn |Collier|1976 |p=136}}\n\n== Named activities ==\n* Bodyline Joint Staff Committee<ref name=Sandys>{{cite web\n  |last=Sandys |first=Duncan |authorlink=Duncan Sandys |date=October\u2013December 1943\n  | title = Reports by Bodyline Joint Staff Committee\n  | url = http://janus.lib.cam.ac.uk/db/node.xsp?id=EAD%2FGBR%2F0014%2FDSND%202%2F4%2F4A | work = The Papers of Lord Duncan-Sandys |publisher=[[Churchill Archives Centre]]\n  | accessdate = 2007-05-09 }}</ref>\n* [[V-1 flying bomb#Countermeasures|Diver]] \u2013 a secret British Defence Instruction specified the code name: \"Enemy Flying Bombs will be referred to or known as 'Diver' aircraft or pilotless planes\" to alert defences of an imminent attack (often called [[Operation Diver]], particularly post-war, without citation).{{sfn|Cooksley|1979|p=61}}\n* Flying Bomb Counter Measures Committee ([[Duncan Sandys]], chairman){{sfn|Cooksley|1979|p=42}}\n* Fuel Panel of the Special Scientific Committee ([[Frank Edward Smith|Sir Frank Smith]], chairman){{Rp|150}}\n* Questionnaire ... to establish the practicability ... of the German Long-Range Rocket (by [[Frederick Lindemann, 1st Viscount Cherwell]]){{Rp|131}}\n\n{{externalimage|align=right|images=\n[http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/AAF/III/maps/AAF-III-2.jpg 1944 Crossbow Network (map)]\n[http://www.allworldwars.com/V-Weapons%20Crossbow%20Campaign.html#10 USSBS Crossbow Exhibits]\n}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== 